[[File:Roman Empire - Africa Proconsularis (125 AD).svg|thumb|[[Roman North Africa|Africa Proconsularis]] (125 AD)]]
'''Gunela''' was an ancient [[Roman Empire|Roman]]-[[Berbers|Berber]] town and archaeological site in [[Bizerte Governorate]], [[Tunisia]]. It was located at 37.165524n, 9.765536e, within the suburbs of [[Tinja, Tunisia]].<ref>''Barrington Atlas'', 32 E2.</ref>

In antiquity, Gunela was a [[civitas|town]] in the province of [[Africa Proconsularis]].<ref>R. B. Hitchner, [https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/314969  Gunela] a Pleiades place resource</ref> Gunela has been tentatively located at the ruins of Henchir-Goungla across the river from [[Tinja, Tunisia|Tindja]].<ref>[http://imperium.ahlfeldt.se/places/28089.html About: Gunela?, Henchir-Goungla]</ref> The town flourished from 30BC to AD640.<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t0906.htm&usg=ALkJrhjn9r8Yat1hG7TA1jDiFd7pLwF6TQ Titular Episcopal See of  Gunela], at GCatholic.org.</ref> 

During [[late antiquity]], Gunela was the [[cathedra|seat]] of an ancient [[Roman Catholic]] [[diocese]],<ref>[[Pius Bonifacius Gams]], ''Series episcoporum Ecclesiae Catholicae'', (Leipzig, 1931), p. 466.</ref><ref>Stefano Antonio Morcelli, ''Africa christiana'', Volume I, (Brescia, 1816), pp.176.</ref> suffragan of the [[Archdiocese of Carthage]]. The only bishop recorded by history is Pascasio, who took part in the [[Council of Carthage (484)]] that was convened by the [[Vandal]] king [[Huneric]], after which Pascasio was exiled. Today it survives as [[titular bishop]]ric and the current archbishop is [[Christophe Pierre]].<ref>[https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com.au&sl=it&sp=nmt4&u=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/d2g67.html&usg=ALkJrhj9nsZvgyA1C1X6EaXNt3TToUQEOg  Gunela] at Catholic-hierarchy.org.</ref><ref>''Le Petit Episcopologe'', Issue 143, Number 12.613. </ref>

